metadata.name: Limina #286
metadata.description:
Limina is a study of the fine line between order and chaos.

Each piece of the collection is made up of just one or two lines. These lines are defined by thousands of points that are chosen, one by one, by a simple algorithm moving across the canvas. What arises from that simple concept is a surprising variety of intricate patterns, accidental symmetries and traces of order in chaotic structures. 

Limina is a meditation on the concept of emergence, a concept that lies at the heart of generative art. The algorithm that defines the core of the series is only capable of making one simple choice: left, right, up or down? As it moves across the canvas, it leaves a trace of points that are connected by a curve. The order in which these points are chosen and the tightness of the curve connecting them is what creates the visual diversity of Limina. As these values fluctuate, symmetries emerge and break down again, forms, patterns and ornaments are created and combined to form both complex structures and simple abstractions. 

Limina shows the potential of minimalist generative concepts to generate visually dense and unexpected results. 

Press 's' to save your image.

metadata.name: Los Osos 2422 #1541
metadata.description:
# Los Osos 2422

I was working on the next EmProps release when accidentally I opened a link to a bear utopic civilization through their existing metaverse. Or should I say "metabears"?

Enter Los Osos 2422. 

Four hundred years into the future bears live in a peaceful civilization heavily inspired by the generative art movement of our times. They are organized in districts that are sustained by bamboo, salmon, berries, and art! Los Osos are black, grizzly, panda, and polar, yet there are no distinctions between species; it's not like they were humans. 

They have different occupations but frequently bears change jobs giving birth to the most eclectic looks.

I took my sketchbook out to capture what I could and started drawing but my presence pissed them off. Ninjas, luchadores, and even a cybearpunk forced me to escape.  Is that a live gummy bear or am I just hungry? The story will continue...

-- 

Los Osos 2422 is a PFP art piece composed of 320 hand-made drawings made as an homage to the nascent generative art current fueled by Tezos blockchain technology in 2022. It features hundreds of references to artists and pieces in several generative and non-generative fields.

The project combines the assets together using a custom open-source algorithm that allows them to stack with the positioning in front and behind the character to create possibilities like shirt collars or hats, dynamic tinting to have hoodies or glasses with different colors, exceptions to give them laser eyes or a green apple in front of the face, complex set-ups to have different versions for some of the outfits, and chance control to allow precise control over the features.

--

Press 'S' on the keyboard to save it as an 1800 x 1800 pixels PNG.

metadata.name: Galactica #7
metadata.description:
Galactica shows us the landscapes of a distant exoplanetary system made up of 10 planets.
Standing on one of these planets with its particular geomorphology, we may see faraway galaxies, natural satellites and/or another planet in the sky.

The combination of the various features can give life to up to 415,000 different versions, taking into account the differences not related to features the versions rise to about 12 billion.

Press "s" to get a 2000x2000 pixels jpg.

Generative artwork by Gandhiavelli, @gandhiavelli. Made with p5js in 2022.
License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Incomplete Convergence #275
metadata.description:
Cutting an optimization process short can lead to interesting results. This series builds on the earlier Sneronoi series but doesn't attempt to run to full convergence. Images are generated by gradient descent and the optimization process is shown as an animation. Each piece is considered final when the animation stops.

There are ten different color palettes, each with four different options for background colors. There are also different shapes drawn in the background and different modes in which the foreground and the background are blended together. In combination, these options result in a wide range of distinct visual outputs. Made with D3.

Press 's' to save as svg.

Press 'p' to save as png (4000x4000).

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

metadata.name: Abstract Life #186
metadata.description:
The concept of organic, obtained from living systems, is said to be an effect that, like a plant and a living being, has grown in a completely dynamic manner in different degrees, and no factor except vital forces has prevented its growth. Organic creation is an example of this type. Léonard de Vinci believed in nature; he wrote, "Painting is a child of nature" in his opinion, art should be compatible with nature. His public image of creativity was "innovation while maintaining fidelity" to nature. According to Michelangelo, the form the artist gives to the materials is in the artist's mind and the materials themselves. Therefore, the artist is always in a metaphysical struggle with the form and secrets of nature. This is a revelatory process through which the artist discovers the mass of paper already hidden in his mind and the materials. As an architect, I tried to create this work while paying attention to the structuralism of shapes and forms in creation, inspired by the colors in nature and my experience in painting and illustration.

To spread the vibe of my beautiful community, minters will own 50% of royalty on each secondary sale.
Eighteen different color palettes and three different borders are used in this artwork.
Made in p5js
Created August 2022
Artist: @ChistaAi

Canyon is a generative art project inspired by canyons and reinterpreted in 9 different styles (that each have their own specificities):

- Radioactive
- Blue Grotto

Accessories (Kayak, Rowing Boat, Barrels) are present on some variations (in this case, it is possible to generate a second variation without accessories by pressing "a").

Made with ❤️, code and p5js.

metadata.name: SWTBD - construction drawing #97
metadata.description:
Construction drawing of the "Several ways to break down" generative geometry system by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut

mouse:

click: toggle active mode. In active mode, a new iteration with the same starting geometry and identical features is generated every 10s.

keyboard:

'a' or 'A' : add a slice or point
'e': decrease explosion factor
'E': increase explosion factor
'r' or 'R': create a new iteration with the same starting geometry and identical features
'+' and '-': zoom in and out
arrow keys: rotate around and translate along the vertical axis

metadata.name: Floating Point  #61
metadata.description:
'Floating Point' by pixelwank 

Inspired by pastel smudging and the aerial photography of Rich Caldwell, Floating Point has impressions of a landscape and other structures. 

Homage to floating point numbers and how just one decimal difference can change it all. 

Floating Point is also the fictional name of the place where this work takes me, where does it take you?

In live mode, click the image or press 's' or 'S' to save 3000x4000 png 

Thanks for collecting 
Shoutout Circolors for the support & frenship <3 

Made with p5js

metadata.name: musical society #619
metadata.description:
society.png: musical society is a collaborative PFP work drawn by Tito Yusuf and directed by Sandy Pirouzi with the aim to facilitate Tezos newcomers with affordable PFP to rock.

This series is taking inspiration from a music scene that Tito is part of. Some traits are paying tribute to some of Tezos musicians such as Jburn, Musical Jackal, Binerica, and Sigmun.

---------------------------------------------
  Most will be us
Some are pretending to be us
Some others are even not us
(And few of them are not even alive anymore)
---------------------------------------------

  PS Tito is a master at bad drawing. Don’t expect fine lines with perfect alignment in his drawing (but the colors are fun!).

  PPS There’s no utility in this project except the CC0 license, so just have fun with it ;)  

Special thanks to:
 purespider for the template and assistance
Jburn, IndraAziz (Musical Jackal), Binerica, Mirffu (Sigmun) for allowing the making and usage of respective traits
ciphrd and fx(hash) team for allowing the making and usage of fx(hash) traits

 Type: Image Composition
 Dimension: 1000 x 1000 px
License for visual: CC0 
License for code: MIT

Twitter: @titoys90 @spirouzi

metadata.name: A Watch #154
metadata.description:
Another adventure in narrated horology: this work features entirely new texts, authored by AI that I trained on a set of novels. Each minute is an AI prose output, a fragment of a novel that doesn't exist, generated from the time itself.

The form factor is ideal for smaller window sizes and displays, although it will scale to any size. With the right device, you could probably wear it on your wrist.

Nearly 5,000 unique text templates are included, many of which feature variable character names, for which I sourced approximately 1.8 million possible first names and 150,000 possible surnames from U.S. Census data: https://github.com/rossgoodwin/american-names

I wanted to provide just enough text for each minute so that you could read the whole excerpt before the minute ends, though you might need to read briskly. None of the passages have been edited manually, and some remain quite glitchy, as intended. You may recognize a few motifs or proper names here and there, depending on the books you're familiar with, but each passage remains wholly original otherwise.

Each edition features either a linear or nonlinear text sequence:

Nonlinear editions will all show one of two possible template texts for each minute, and will read like fragments from multiple (strange and glitchy) novels. Nonlinear sequences feature independently generated texts, with variable character names unique to each minute of each edition.

Linear editions will all show the same template text for each minute, and will read like (strange and glitchy) 24-hour novels. For linear sequences, I utilized a generative prompting technique in which each minute's text is generated partially from the text of the minute before it. Variable character names for linear sequences are unique to each edition and repeat throughout the day.

Aesthetic possibilities for each edition include 16 color palettes, 8 fonts, 7 depths, 5 types of numerals, and 3 types of hands. Some editions have color-accented second hands and minute marks, while others appear more static and minimalist, without any numerals or second hand at all.

This token relies on p5.js for the clockwork, vanilla JS for the text.



Double click to toggle fullscreen.

Push `d` to download current minute's text as a .txt file.
